{{Infobox person | name = Ye Zheyun | birth_place = [[China]] | disappeared_date = November 2005 (age 40) }} '''Ye Zheyun''' is a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] [[businessman]] who was accused of being involved in a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Association football|football]] [[Political corruption|corruption]] and [[Gambling|betting]] [[List of sporting scandals|scandal]] in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expatica.com/be/news/Belgian-soccer-match-fixing-scandal-widens_133915.html|title=Belgian soccer match-fixing scandal widens|access-date=2017-09-15}}</ref> It was alleged that several teams and/or players received money from Ye to [[Match fixing|influence match results]], so involved gamblers could be certain of a gambling profit.
==Background information== Teams mentioned in the scandal are [[Lierse S.K.|Lierse]], [[R.A.A. Louviéroise|La Louvière]], [[K. Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truiden]], [[R.A.E.C. Mons|Mons]], [[K.F.C. Verbroedering Geel|Geel]] and also [[Beerschot AC|Germinal Beerschot]]. Ye always appeared at teams with financial problems, except for Beerschot, who had at that time a crucial match against AEC Mons who were on the verge of relegation. The insinuations about fixed results started after a few matches, on which were heavily betted, with strange events and/or results. Such as e.g. Lierse starting with a reserve team twice unexpectedly. Ye had also been the owner of [[Finland|Finnish]] team [[AC Allianssi]], due to [[bankruptcy]] a now defunct club who also seemed to experience from some strange match events at the end of their existence. Police investigated the case but found insufficient evidence.
==Disappearance== Ye mostly worked together with Pietro Allatta and [[Olivier Suray]]. Police arrested both, but Allatta and Suray were released after interrogation. On 16 March the Belgian [[Federal Public Service Justice|Justice Department]] ordered an international [[arrest warrant]] against Ye. It is unknown where he currently remains. His [[lawyer]] told [[France|French]] [[sports]] [[newspaper|paper]] ''[[L'Équipe]]'' that Ye denied all accusations and that he was residing somewhere in [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/03/sports/soccer-corruption-without-borders-in-belgian-scandals-china-link.html|title=Soccer: Corruption without borders in Belgian scandal's China link|date=2006-03-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9906E2DB1330F935A35751C1A96F9C8B63|title=Police Look at Links to Soccer Betting in Murders in England|last=Werdigier|first=Julia|date=2009-12-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-15|last2=Newcastle|first2=ROB HUGHES; Julia Werdigier reported from|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=London|first3=Rob Hughes from|last4=Bochum|last5=Germany.}}</ref>
